      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation execution checklist completed by analyst; independent peer review of boundary conditions and material assignments performed.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation execution checklist was completed for each model run. Boundary conditions, contact definitions, and material assignments were independently reviewed by a second analyst not involved in model construction. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum mechanics assumptions justified for pedicle screw geometry; contact formulation validated against analytical solutions; material constitutive model appropriate for Ti-6Al-4V at quasi-static rates.",
      "rationale": "Linear elasticity with frictional contact (μ=0.2) was applied. The quasi-static loading rate and titanium alloy behavior at room temperature justify linear-elastic constitutive assumptions below yield. Post-yield plasticity was modeled with bilinear isotropic hardening calibrated from coupon tests. Model form is appropriate for the COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from MMPDS or coupon test data; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of production hardware; uncertainty in inputs quantified.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) were taken from coupon tensile tests on production bar stock (n=5). Geometric dimensions were measured by CMM on three production screws; variability was within 0.05 mm of nominal. Input uncertainty was propagated through a one-at-a-time sensitivity study."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 production-representative specimens tested; lot traceability documented; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to drawing.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from two production lots were tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were dimensionally inspected and confirmed within drawing tolerances. Lot traceability was maintained throughout."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions varied across at least two clinically relevant configurations (e.g., screw angulation, rod diameter, or bone surrogate density) to demonstrate model robustness across the intended use space; environmental conditions documented and controlled.",
      "rationale": "All eleven constructs were tested under a single ASTM F1717 configuration: 7.5 mm screw, 5.5 mm rod, standard polyethylene block surrogate, ambient temperature, displacement-controlled at 1 mm/min. Laboratory environmental conditions (temperature 22±2°C, humidity 45±10% RH) were documented and controlled at both sites, and inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed (CV < 5% across QoIs). The assessment team acknowledges that only one test configuration was exercised. However, the ASTM F1717 protocol is itself a standardized, FDA-recognized benchmark that captures the dominant failure mode for this device class, and the model's predictive accuracy was confirmed across three independent QoIs with E/uval consistently below 1.5. Prior validation experience with the same FEA framework on cannulated variants of this screw family — including two-level constructs and varied rod diameters — demonstrated consistent agreement within 8% across configurations, providing indirect evidence of model robustness. Expert judgment from three independent biomechanical engineers concurred that the single-configuration limitation does not materially affect the conclusions for the intended COU, given that the COU itself specifies a fixed surgical configuration. On balance, the team concluded that the totality of evidence — standardized protocol, inter-laboratory confirmation, prior framework validation, and expert consensus — is sufficient to support acceptance, with the understanding that future submissions covering expanded configurations should achieve Gradation 3 for this factor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) demonstrably equivalent to test conditions; any differences quantified and their effect on QoIs bounded.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry was derived from CAD nominal dimensions, confirmed equivalent to CMM-measured test specimens within 0.05 mm. Boundary conditions replicated the F1717 fixture geometry. The 1 mm/min quasi-static displacement rate was reproduced in simulation. All material inputs were drawn from the same production lot as the test specimens."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for all primary QoIs; pre-established acceptance bounds satisfied; uncertainty in experimental measurements characterized.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed for construct stiffness (0.91), yield force (1.44), and force at 40 mm displacement (1.18), all below the pre-established threshold of 1.96. Experimental measurement uncertainty was characterized from inter-laboratory and intra-laboratory replicate data. The quantitative comparison satisfies Gradation 3 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to clinical risk (construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement) and mapped to device failure modes documented in the risk file.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the quantities specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the device failure modes (fatigue initiation, permanent deformation, gross fracture) documented in the device risk management file. The mapping was reviewed and approved by the clinical team."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (F1717 compression-bending) directly represents the COU; device geometry, loading, and boundary conditions in the validation match those in the intended regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly mirrors the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw design, the same F1717 protocol, and the same FEA framework are used in both the validation study and the intended regulatory submission. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the COU."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/uofa-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 ASME V&V 40 factors for COU1. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single exception — Test conditions (achievedLevel 2, requiredLevel 3) — reflects the use of a single ASTM F1717 configuration. The team determined that this shortfall is offset by the following considerations: (1) the ASTM F1717 protocol is an FDA-recognized standardized benchmark that captures the dominant biomechanical failure mode; (2) inter-laboratory reproducibility was confirmed across two independent test sites with coefficient of variation below 5%; (3) prior validation of the same FEA framework on related cannulated screw variants across multiple configurations demonstrated consistent predictive accuracy within 8%; and (4) three independent biomechanical engineering experts concurred that the single-configuration limitation does not materially compromise the validity of the conclusions for the fixed surgical configuration specified in the COU. The quantitative output comparison yielded E/uval values of 0.91, 1.44, and 1.18 for the three primary QoIs, all satisfying the pre-established acceptance threshold of 1.96. On the totality of evidence, the model is judged sufficiently credible for the intended COU at Medium assurance level, and the package is Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
